But I&#39;ve been seeing the biggest jumps coming out of the longest
stagnations. 
I&#39;ve been running the algorithm on the fractional derivative I was
talking about earlier, and even though I haven&#39;t found any good
solutions yet, I&#39;ve been making many many runs with different starting
conditions. One interesting thing is that the large populations ( 500 -
4000 ) tend to have more consistent slopes, and when they stagnate, they
will make large jumps out of the stagnation, and continue improving. The
smaller populations seldom jump out of the stagnation before the
predefined number of generations finish running. (usually about 1000). 
And thanks ken for breaking my coevolution cycle of increasing the rate
at which nodes were added. I just kept cranking it up and up and I
didn&#39;t notice it was getting worse and worse. I put it back to 5% and
increased the number of species, and performance was more consistent. 
An interesting issue with the big populations and fast mutations is that
when the size of 2000 members triples, there is a noticeable difference
in the pace. Within 150 generations, an epoch went from ~30 seconds to
over an hour. wow. I havn&#39;t profiled to see how much was NEAT and how
much was the fitness, but I would guess over 50% of that time was spent
in network activation. I&#39;ll try and profile that in the near future, but
all the discussion earlier about accelerated activation seems more
usefull now. (I was also using the tanh() function from the math
library, not a slope aproximation algorithm)

on a side note, I&#39;d like to hear some ideas about how to implement
bilateral/multilateral symmetry. After reading the site on the link
posted earlier, I am very curious, but he doesn&#39;t post his code. 

Chad 

