Quoting John Arrowwood :

&gt;&gt;From: Colin Green 
&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;As for the idea of pruning a stagnant species, that&#39;s not all that
&gt;&gt;&gt;good...when you start going forward again, you would undo your
pruning as
&gt;&gt;&gt;you look for a way to move forward. You would need to wait until the
&gt;&gt;&gt;stagnant species has broken out of that stagnation, and THEN prune.
But 
&gt;&gt;I
&gt;&gt;&gt;think your best bet is to wait until you have found an acceptable 
&gt;&gt;solution,
&gt;&gt;&gt;and then do a phase that supports pruning in order to optimize that
&gt;&gt;&gt;solution.
&gt;&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;
&gt;&gt;Yes that makes more sense :) So if some of the neutral structure
&gt;&gt;becomes positive then you have moved into a new and better position in
&gt;&gt;the overall search space, this warrants searching around that space
for
&gt;&gt;a while, but! you are still likely to have some of the neutral
structure
&gt;&gt;that didn&#39;t become positive. This means you are searching through a
&gt;&gt;higher search dimensionality than you really should be - you have
found
&gt;&gt;a new promising point in the search space so you don&#39;t really want
that
&gt;&gt;speculative neutral structure, not until you start to stagnate again.
&gt;&gt;Therefore I think it would be a refinement of the NEAT search process
to
&gt;&gt;prune neutral structure from the genomes at that point.
&gt; 
&gt; My question is, which is more expensive? Continuing to search in the
higher
&gt; 
&gt; space, with the ability to coopt neutral structure into useful, or the
&gt; pruning pass followed by a forward search that must then perhaps
re-add 
&gt; structure?

Certainly if you did a prune phase upon every single improvement I can
imagine 
this would be very inefficient. I remember now that this is why I
suggested 
pruning only after a period of stagnation... the theory being that you
just 
leave the neutral structure and continue searching in the higher space
while it 
is still working. If you then reach a point of stagnation *then* prune
your way 
back to the lower search space - which could be quite a bit lower for
the first 
prune.

Of course if you did this and still stagnated then you wouldn&#39;t want to
trigger 
off another prune phase, there would be no point. So perhaps if we set a
flag 
that tells us that pruning is an option, and which gets set to true
whenever an 
improvement is found. So when stagnation does occur we check the flag
first 
before deciding to prune.

Colin.







